  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety and stress that individuals from underrepresented groups experience when they are reminded of negative stereotypes about their group’s abilities in science, technology, engineering, or mathematics. For someone like me, who grew up in a household where both parents were highly educated but never in STEM fields, I’ve seen firsthand how this dynamic plays out. My own experience as a part-time waiter in Los Angeles has taught me that people often feel the weight of expectations without realizing it. When I talk to young folks at the counter who are considering STEM careers, I notice they sometimes hesitate because they fear being judged or failing due to perceived biases. This is stereotype threat in action. It’s not just about the fear of being labeled but the internalized pressure that can lead to underperformance. As someone who’s anxious, I know how much stress can derail even the simplest tasks—so I can empathize with the mental toll this phenomenon takes. Addressing it requires more than just awareness; it needs concrete steps like mentorship programs, inclusive classroom environments, and early exposure to diverse role models. In my community, where I spend time reading novels and taking photos, I’ve seen how storytelling and visual media can help break down barriers. But the real solution lies in systemic change—ensuring that every child, regardless of background, feels safe to explore their interests without fear of judgment. We must act now, not because it’s morally right, but because it’s practical: when people feel valued, they perform better. The stakes are too high for anyone to ignore.",
